<article title='Amalric'><paragraph><bold>Amalric</bold><space/>or<space/><bold>Amalaric</bold><space/>(also Americ, Almerich, Emeric, Emerick and other variations) is a personal name derived from the tribal name<space/><italics>Amal</italics><space/>(referring to the Gothic<space/><link><target>Amali</target></link>) and<space/><italics>ric</italics><space/>(<link><target>Gothic language</target><part>Gothic</part></link><space/><italics>reiks</italics>) meaning &quot;ruler, prince&quot;.<space/></paragraph><paragraph>Equivalents in different languages include:</paragraph><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>French language</target><part>French</part></link>: Amaury (surname/given name), Amalric (surname), Amaurich (surname), Maury (surname)</listitem><listitem><link><target>German language</target><part>German</part></link>: Amalrich, Emmerich.</listitem><listitem><link><target>Italian language</target><part>Italian</part></link>:<space/><link><target>Amerigo (disambiguation)</target><part>Amerigo</part></link>,<space/><link><target>Arrigo (disambiguation)</target><part>Arrigo</part></link>.</listitem><listitem><link><target>Hungarian language</target><part>Hungarian</part></link>: Imre.</listitem><listitem><link><target>Latin</target></link>: Amalricus, Americus, Almericus, Emericus.</listitem><listitem><link><target>Greek language</target><part>Greek</part></link>: Emerikos.</listitem><listitem><link><target>Polish language</target><part>Polish</part></link>: Amalaryk, Amalryk, Emeryk.</listitem><listitem><link><target>Portuguese language</target><part>Portuguese</part></link>: Amauri, Amrico, Amrica.</listitem><listitem><link><target>Spanish language</target><part>Spanish</part></link>: Amrico.</listitem></list><heading level='2'>Given name</heading><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>Amalaric</target></link>, King of the Visigoths from 526 to 531</listitem><listitem><link><target>Malaric</target></link>, King of the Suevi 585</listitem><listitem><link><target>Amalric of Nesle</target></link>, Patriarch of Jerusalem from 1158 to 1180</listitem><listitem><link><target>Amalric I of Jerusalem</target></link>, King of Jerusalem from 1162 to 1174</listitem><listitem><link><target>Amalric II of Jerusalem</target></link>, King of Jerusalem from 1197 to 1205</listitem><listitem><link><target>Amalric of Bena</target></link>, French theologian ca. 1200</listitem><listitem><link><target>Arnaud Amalric</target></link>, seventeenth abbot of Citeaux, died 1225</listitem><listitem><link><target>Amalric, Prince of Tyre</target></link>, Governor of Cyprus from 1306 to 1310</listitem></list><paragraph><template><target>given name</target></template></paragraph><heading level='2'>Surname</heading><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>Mathieu Amalric</target></link>, French actor and director born in 1965</listitem><listitem><link><target>Leonid Amalrik</target></link><space/>(19051997), Soviet animator</listitem><listitem><link><target>Andrei Amalrik</target></link><space/>(19381980), Soviet dissident</listitem></list><heading level='2'>See also</heading><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>Amaury (disambiguation)</target><part>Amaury</part></link>, a French alternate spelling</listitem><listitem><link><target>Emery (name)</target></link></listitem></list><paragraph><template><target>surname</target></template></paragraph><paragraph><link><target>Category:Masculine given names</target></link></paragraph></article>